Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lua Parser - Complete AST generation for Lua language
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Handles all Lua syntax including tables, metatables, coroutines, varargs
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/lua/lua_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Program structure
Constant LUA_PROGRAM as Integer is 1000
Constant LUA_BLOCK as Integer is 1001

Note: Declarations
Constant LUA_FUNCTION as Integer is 1100
Constant LUA_LOCAL_DECLARATION as Integer is 1101
Constant LUA_ASSIGNMENT as Integer is 1102

Note: Statements
Constant LUA_IF_STATEMENT as Integer is 1200
Constant LUA_WHILE_STATEMENT as Integer is 1201
Constant LUA_REPEAT_STATEMENT as Integer is 1202
Constant LUA_FOR_NUMERIC as Integer is 1203
Constant LUA_FOR_GENERIC as Integer is 1204
Constant LUA_FUNCTION_CALL as Integer is 1205
Constant LUA_RETURN_STATEMENT as Integer is 1206
Constant LUA_BREAK_STATEMENT as Integer is 1207
Constant LUA_LABEL_STATEMENT as Integer is 1208
Constant LUA_GOTO_STATEMENT as Integer is 1209

Note: Expressions
Constant LUA_BINARY_OP as Integer is 1300
Constant LUA_UNARY_OP as Integer is 1301
Constant LUA_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 1302
Constant LUA_NUMBER_LITERAL as Integer is 1303
Constant LUA_STRING_LITERAL as Integer is 1304
Constant LUA_BOOLEAN_LITERAL as Integer is 1305
Constant LUA_NIL_LITERAL as Integer is 1306
Constant LUA_TABLE_CONSTRUCTOR as Integer is 1307
Constant LUA_FUNCTION_EXPRESSION as Integer is 1308
Constant LUA_VARARG as Integer is 1309
Constant LUA_INDEX_ACCESS as Integer is 1310
Constant LUA_FIELD_ACCESS as Integer is 1311

Note: Table fields
Constant LUA_TABLE_FIELD as Integer is 1400
Constant LUA_TABLE_FIELD_NAMED as Integer is 1401
Constant LUA_TABLE_FIELD_INDEXED as Integer is 1402

Note: Parameter lists
Constant LUA_PARAMETER_LIST as Integer is 1500
Constant LUA_ARGUMENT_LIST as Integer is 1501
Constant LUA_NAME_LIST as Integer is 1502
Constant LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST as Integer is 1503

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Captures everything the parser needs across calls: the token list, the
current cursor, a sticky has_error flag plus message, and the AST node
arena. Field-based struct (not a raw layout block) because Lua parser
uses memory_read/memory_write with full record copies.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Struct constructed via "a value of type"; allocated on heap via
memory_allocate(size_of LuaParserState). tokens is a List handle of
LuaToken records. current is the 0-based token index. had_error and
error_message track first-error state. ast_nodes is a list of
allocated LuaASTNode handles for bulk cleanup.
@End Implementation

Type called "LuaParserState":
    tokens as Integer              Note: List of tokens
    current as Integer             Note: Current token index
    had_error as Integer           Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
    error_message as String
    ast_nodes as Integer           Note: List of AST nodes
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single AST node shape covering every Lua construct. value is a String
(for identifier names and literal text); line/column carry source
position; children is a flat list for positional sub-nodes; metadata
is a dictionary for kind-specific attributes (e.g. boolean flags on
local declarations).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
6-field struct allocated via memory_allocate(size_of LuaASTNode).
node_type uses the LUA_* constants. children and metadata are List
handles created in create_ast_node so every node is fully initialised
on construction.
@End Implementation

Type called "LuaASTNode":
    node_type as Integer
    value as String
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    children as Integer            Note: List of child nodes
    metadata as Integer            Note: Dictionary for additional data
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Initialization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates parser state pre-loaded with the token stream produced by
the lexer. Begins at index 0 with no errors and an empty AST-node
arena.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Constructs LuaParserState struct via "a value of type" with tokens
set, current=0, had_error=0, empty error_message, and a fresh
ast_nodes list. Struct construction allocates the heap home directly
and the binding is the struct pointer. Returns that pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_parser" takes tokens as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create and initialize a new Lua parser state.
    @End Reasoning

    Let parser be a value of type LuaParserState with
        tokens as tokens,
        current as 0,
        had_error as 0,
        error_message as "",
        ast_nodes as proc list_create from ListCore

    Return parser
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single constructor that initialises every AST node — including the
children and metadata lists — so callers can attach children
immediately without worrying about lazy creation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a LuaASTNode with the supplied node_type, empty value string,
zero line/column, and freshly allocated children and metadata lists.
Struct construction allocates the heap home directly and the binding
is the struct pointer. Returns that pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_ast_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a new AST node with the given type.
    @End Reasoning

    Let node be a value of type LuaASTNode with
        node_type as node_type,
        value as "",
        line as 0,
        column as 0,
        children as proc list_create from ListCore,
        metadata as proc list_create from ListCore

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Appends a child to the parent's children list. Must round-trip the
parent record through memory_read/memory_write because LuaASTNode is
stored by value at node_ptr.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the node struct from node_ptr. Appends child_ptr to
node.children via ListCore.list_append. Writes the struct back so
the updated list-handle (if reallocated) is observed by future reads.
@End Implementation

Process called "ast_node_add_child" takes node_ptr as Integer, child_ptr as Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Add a child node to an AST node.
    @End Reasoning

    Let node as LuaASTNode be node_ptr
    proc list_append from ListCore with node.children, child_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Updates the .value field on an existing node. Round-trips the struct
through memory_read/memory_write because nodes are stored inline at
their pointers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the node, assigns value to node.value, writes the node back.
@End Implementation

Process called "ast_node_set_value" takes node_ptr as Integer, value as String:
    @Reasoning
    Set the value of an AST node.
    @End Reasoning

    Let node as LuaASTNode be node_ptr
    Set node.value to value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records the source position of a node for diagnostic reporting.
Called by every parse_* helper right after node creation to attach
location info from the consumed token.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the node, sets node.line and node.column from the parameters,
writes the node back.
@End Implementation

Process called "ast_node_set_location" takes node_ptr as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Set the source location of an AST node.
    @End Reasoning

    Let node as LuaASTNode be node_ptr
    Set node.line to line
    Set node.column to column
End Process

@Reasoning:
Indexed child accessor. Read-only — does not mutate the node, so no
memory_write needed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the node struct; reads children list; returns list_get at the
given index. Out-of-range indices are the caller's responsibility.
@End Implementation

Process called "ast_node_get_child" takes node_ptr as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Get a child node by index.
    @End Reasoning

    Let node as LuaASTNode be node_ptr
    Let child be proc list_get from ListCore with node.children, index
    Return child
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reports the child count for iteration loops. Used pervasively by
traversal code that wants to walk a node's children.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the node; returns list_length of the children list.
@End Implementation

Process called "ast_node_child_count" takes node_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Get the number of children in an AST node.
    @End Reasoning

    Let node as LuaASTNode be node_ptr
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with node.children
    Return count
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Navigation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Returns the token under the parser cursor. Guards against past-end
access by returning the last token (typically the EOF sentinel emitted
by the lexer) so callers can safely dispatch on its type without
bounds-checking each call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads parser struct, fetches token count, returns token at
parser.current — or the last token if current is at or past the end
of the stream.
@End Implementation

Process called "current_token" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Get the current token.
    @End Reasoning

    Let parser as LuaParserState be parser_ptr
    Let token_count be proc list_length from ListCore with parser.tokens

    If parser.current is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Note: Return EOF token
        Let last_token be proc list_get from ListCore with parser.tokens, token_count minus 1
        Return last_token
    End If

    Let token be proc list_get from ListCore with parser.tokens, parser.current
    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lookahead variant of current_token: returns the token at
current + offset without consuming. Used to disambiguate constructs
that share a prefix (e.g. `function name(` vs `function(`).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads parser; computes peek_index = current + offset; returns the
last token if past end, otherwise the token at peek_index. No
mutation.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_token" takes parser_ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Look ahead at a token without consuming it.
    @End Reasoning

    Let parser as LuaParserState be parser_ptr
    Let token_count be proc list_length from ListCore with parser.tokens
    Let peek_index be parser.current plus offset

    If peek_index is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Note: Return EOF token
        Let last_token be proc list_get from ListCore with parser.tokens, token_count minus 1
        Return last_token
    End If

    Let token be proc list_get from ListCore with parser.tokens, peek_index
    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes the current token and steps the cursor forward. Returns the
just-consumed token so the caller can capture its lexeme/location
without an extra read. Stays put once past end-of-stream.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads parser; captures current_token via current_token helper.
Increments parser.current only when not yet at end. Writes parser
back. Returns the captured token.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Advance to the next token and return the previous token.
    @End Reasoning

    Let parser as LuaParserState be parser_ptr
    Let current_tok be proc current_token with parser_ptr

    Let token_count be proc list_length from ListCore with parser.tokens
    If parser.current is less than token_count:
        Set parser.current to parser.current plus 1
    End If

    Return current_tok
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-consuming "is current token of type X" predicate. Used as the
gate for optional grammar rules.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Fetches the current token; reads its struct; returns 1 if
tok.token_type matches token_type, 0 otherwise. No mutation.
@End Implementation

Process called "check" takes parser_ptr as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Check if the current token is of the given type.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token be proc current_token with parser_ptr
    Let tok as Lexer.LuaToken be token

    If tok.token_type is equal to token_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consume-on-match helper. Returns 1 + advances if the current token
matches expected_type, returns 0 + no advance otherwise. Used for
optional tokens (commas, semicolons, optional keywords).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls check; on match (1) calls advance and returns 1. On mismatch
returns 0 with no side effects.
@End Implementation

Process called "match" takes parser_ptr as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Check if the current token matches the given type and advance if it does.
    @End Reasoning

    If proc check with parser_ptr, token_type is equal to 1:
        proc advance with parser_ptr
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mandatory-token gate. On match, advances and returns the consumed
token so callers can use it. On mismatch, records the error and
returns the current token so the parser can attempt recovery rather
than crash.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls check. If 1, calls advance and returns the consumed token.
Otherwise calls parser_error with the supplied message and returns
the current token (without advancing).
@End Implementation

Process called "consume" takes parser_ptr as Integer, token_type as Integer, error_message as String returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Consume a token of the expected type or report an error.
    @End Reasoning

    If proc check with parser_ptr, token_type is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc advance with parser_ptr
        Return token
    End If

    proc parser_error with parser_ptr, error_message
    Set token to proc current_token with parser_ptr
    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Sticky-error recorder. Once set, had_error stays at 1 so callers can
short-circuit subsequent parse logic. Last-error wins on the message
field because the most informative diagnostic is typically the most
recent one.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads parser; sets had_error=1 and error_message=message; writes back.
@End Implementation

Process called "parser_error" takes parser_ptr as Integer, message as String:
    @Reasoning
    Record a parser error.
    @End Reasoning

    Let parser as LuaParserState be parser_ptr
    Set parser.had_error to 1
    Set parser.error_message to message
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Bottom of the Lua expression grammar: nil/true/false/number/string
literals, vararg `...`, table constructors `{...}`, function
expressions, parenthesised expressions, and bare identifiers. Above
this layer the precedence climbing functions wrap operands in
operators.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sequential If/match chain consuming the matching token and producing
the corresponding LUA_*_LITERAL node. Number/string literals capture
literal_value from the token. Table constructors and function
expressions delegate to dedicated helpers. Parenthesised expression
recurses parse_expression and consumes the closing `)`. Identifiers
build LUA_IDENTIFIER nodes. Falls through to a parser_error with
"Expected expression" and returns a nil-literal placeholder so the
caller does not crash on a null pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_primary" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a primary expression (literals, identifiers, parenthesized expressions).
    @End Reasoning

    Note: nil
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_NIL is equal to 1:
        Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_NIL_LITERAL
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, "nil"
        Return node
    End If

    Note: true
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_TRUE is equal to 1:
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_BOOLEAN_LITERAL
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, "true"
        Return node
    End If

    Note: false
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_FALSE is equal to 1:
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_BOOLEAN_LITERAL
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, "false"
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Number literal
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_NUMBER is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc advance with parser_ptr
        Let tok as Lexer.LuaToken be token
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_NUMBER_LITERAL
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, tok.literal_value
        Return node
    End If

    Note: String literal
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_STRING is equal to 1:
        Set token to proc advance with parser_ptr
        Set tok to token
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_STRING_LITERAL
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, tok.literal_value
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Vararg ...
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DOT_DOT_DOT is equal to 1:
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_VARARG
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, "..."
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Table constructor
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_table_constructor with parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Function expression
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_function_expression with parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Parenthesized expression
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN is equal to 1:
        Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')' after expression"
        Return expr
    End If

    Note: Identifier
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER is equal to 1:
        Set token to proc advance with parser_ptr
        Set tok to token
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, tok.lexeme
        Return node
    End If

    proc parser_error with parser_ptr, "Expected expression"
    Let error_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_NIL_LITERAL
    Return error_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Postfix operations chain left-to-right after a primary: `.field`,
`[index]`, `(args)` calls, and `:method(args)` method calls. Each
operation wraps the current expression as the operand of a new
node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses a primary as starting `expr`. Loops on current token:
TOKEN_DOT consumes and builds LUA_FIELD_ACCESS with the next
identifier; TOKEN_LBRACKET builds LUA_INDEX with the bracketed
expression; TOKEN_LPAREN or TOKEN_STRING/TOKEN_LBRACE call-without-
parens build LUA_FUNCTION_CALL with parsed arguments; TOKEN_COLON
builds LUA_METHOD_CALL with the method name + arguments. Breaks
when no postfix token follows. Returns the assembled expression.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_postfix" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse postfix expressions (function calls, indexing, field access).
    @End Reasoning

    Let expr be proc parse_primary with parser_ptr

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        Note: Function call
        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN is equal to 1:
            Let call_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_FUNCTION_CALL
            proc ast_node_add_child with call_node, expr

            Note: Parse arguments
            Let args be proc parse_argument_list with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with call_node, args

            proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')' after arguments"
            Set expr to call_node
        Otherwise:
            Note: Table constructor call (Lua syntax sugar)
            If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE is equal to 1:
                Set call_node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_FUNCTION_CALL
                proc ast_node_add_child with call_node, expr

                Let arg_list be proc create_ast_node with LUA_ARGUMENT_LIST
                Let table_arg be proc parse_table_constructor with parser_ptr
                proc ast_node_add_child with arg_list, table_arg

                proc ast_node_add_child with call_node, arg_list
                Set expr to call_node
            Otherwise:
                Note: String literal call (Lua syntax sugar)
                If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_STRING is equal to 1:
                    Set call_node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_FUNCTION_CALL
                    proc ast_node_add_child with call_node, expr

                    Set arg_list to proc create_ast_node with LUA_ARGUMENT_LIST
                    Let string_arg be proc parse_primary with parser_ptr
                    proc ast_node_add_child with arg_list, string_arg

                    proc ast_node_add_child with call_node, arg_list
                    Set expr to call_node
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Method call with :
                    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COLON is equal to 1:
                        Let method_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected method name after ':'"
                        Let method_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be method_token

                        Set call_node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_FUNCTION_CALL

                        Note: Create field access for the method
                        Let field_access be proc create_ast_node with LUA_FIELD_ACCESS
                        proc ast_node_add_child with field_access, expr

                        Let method_name be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
                        proc ast_node_set_value with method_name, method_tok.lexeme
                        proc ast_node_add_child with field_access, method_name

                        proc ast_node_add_child with call_node, field_access

                        Note: Parse arguments (self is implicit first argument)
                        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN, "Expected '(' after method name"
                        Set args to proc parse_argument_list with parser_ptr
                        proc ast_node_add_child with call_node, args
                        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')' after arguments"

                        Set expr to call_node
                    Otherwise:
                        Note: Index access [...]
                        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET is equal to 1:
                            Let index_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_INDEX_ACCESS
                            proc ast_node_add_child with index_node, expr

                            Let index_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
                            proc ast_node_add_child with index_node, index_expr

                            proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET, "Expected ']' after index"
                            Set expr to index_node
                        Otherwise:
                            Note: Field access .field
                            If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DOT is equal to 1:
                                Let field_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected field name after '.'"
                                Let field_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be field_token

                                Let field_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_FIELD_ACCESS
                                proc ast_node_add_child with field_node, expr

                                Let field_name be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
                                proc ast_node_set_value with field_name, field_tok.lexeme
                                proc ast_node_add_child with field_node, field_name

                                Set expr to field_node
                            Otherwise:
                                Set continue to 0
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua's prefix operators: `not`, `-` (negate), `#` (length), `~` (bitwise
not). Right-associative — recursing into parse_unary itself for the
operand makes `not not x` work correctly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Checks for each prefix token (NOT, MINUS, HASH, TILDE). On match,
captures operator, advances, recurses parse_unary for the operand,
builds a LUA_UNARY_EXPRESSION node with the operator string and the
operand as child. Otherwise delegates to parse_postfix.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_unary" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse unary expressions (not, -, #, ~).
    @End Reasoning

    Note: not
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_NOT is equal to 1:
        Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_UNARY_OP
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, "not"
        Let operand be proc parse_unary with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with node, operand
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Unary minus
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_MINUS is equal to 1:
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_UNARY_OP
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, "-"
        Set operand to proc parse_unary with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with node, operand
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Length operator #
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_HASH is equal to 1:
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_UNARY_OP
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, "#"
        Set operand to proc parse_unary with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with node, operand
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Bitwise NOT ~
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_TILDE is equal to 1:
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_UNARY_OP
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, "~"
        Set operand to proc parse_unary with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with node, operand
        Return node
    End If

    Return proc parse_postfix with parser_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exponentiation `^` is right-associative in Lua: `2^3^2` parses as
`2^(3^2)`. Recurse into parse_power itself for the right operand to
express the right-association rather than left-association.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses parse_unary as left. If current token is CARET, builds
LUA_BINARY_OP with value "^", attaches left as child, recurses
parse_power for the right operand, attaches right. Returns the binary
node or the bare left if no `^` follows.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_power" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse power expressions (right-associative ^).
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_unary with parser_ptr

    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_CARET is equal to 1:
        Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, "^"
        proc ast_node_add_child with node, left

        Note: Right-associative
        Let right be proc parse_power with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
        Return node
    End If

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multiplicative precedence layer: `*`, `/`, `//` (floor div), `%`.
Left-associative chain over parse_power operands.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses parse_power as left. Loop consumes any of STAR, SLASH,
DOUBLE_SLASH, PERCENT, recursing parse_power for each right operand,
wrapping in LUA_BINARY_OP with the matching operator string,
rebinding left. Returns the left-associated tree.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_multiplicative" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse multiplicative expressions (*, /, //, %).
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_power with parser_ptr

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_STAR is equal to 1:
            Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
            proc ast_node_set_value with node, "*"
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
            Let right be proc parse_power with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
            Set left to node
        Otherwise:
            If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_SLASH_SLASH is equal to 1:
                Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
                proc ast_node_set_value with node, "//"
                proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
                Set right to proc parse_power with parser_ptr
                proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
                Set left to node
            Otherwise:
                If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_SLASH is equal to 1:
                    Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
                    proc ast_node_set_value with node, "/"
                    proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
                    Set right to proc parse_power with parser_ptr
                    proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
                    Set left to node
                Otherwise:
                    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_PERCENT is equal to 1:
                        Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
                        proc ast_node_set_value with node, "%"
                        proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
                        Set right to proc parse_power with parser_ptr
                        proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
                        Set left to node
                    Otherwise:
                        Set continue to 0
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Additive precedence layer: `+` and `-` binary operators.
Left-associative chain over parse_multiplicative operands.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses parse_multiplicative as left. Loop consumes PLUS or MINUS,
recursing parse_multiplicative for right operand, builds
LUA_BINARY_OP with operator string, rebinds left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_additive" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse additive expressions (+, -).
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_multiplicative with parser_ptr

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_PLUS is equal to 1:
            Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
            proc ast_node_set_value with node, "+"
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
            Let right be proc parse_multiplicative with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
            Set left to node
        Otherwise:
            If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_MINUS is equal to 1:
                Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
                proc ast_node_set_value with node, "-"
                proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
                Set right to proc parse_multiplicative with parser_ptr
                proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
                Set left to node
            Otherwise:
                Set continue to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua's `..` concatenation is right-associative per the reference
manual; the right operand therefore recurses parse_concatenation
itself.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses parse_additive as left. If current token is DOT_DOT, builds
LUA_BINARY_OP with operator "..", attaches left, recurses
parse_concatenation for right, attaches right.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_concatenation" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse concatenation expressions (right-associative ..).
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_additive with parser_ptr

    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DOT_DOT is equal to 1:
        Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
        proc ast_node_set_value with node, ".."
        proc ast_node_add_child with node, left

        Note: Right-associative
        Let right be proc parse_concatenation with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
        Return node
    End If

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bitwise shift precedence layer: `<<` (left shift) and `>>` (right
shift), left-associative.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses parse_concatenation as left. Loops on LEFT_SHIFT or RIGHT_SHIFT
tokens, recursing parse_concatenation for right operand each iteration,
wrapping in LUA_BINARY_OP with the matching operator string, rebinding
left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_bitwise_shift" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse bitwise shift expressions (<<, >>).
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_concatenation with parser_ptr

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LT_LT is equal to 1:
            Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
            proc ast_node_set_value with node, "<<"
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
            Let right be proc parse_concatenation with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
            Set left to node
        Otherwise:
            If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_GT_GT is equal to 1:
                Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
                proc ast_node_set_value with node, ">>"
                proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
                Set right to proc parse_concatenation with parser_ptr
                proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
                Set left to node
            Otherwise:
                Set continue to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Relational and equality operators: `<`, `>`, `<=`, `>=`, `==`, and
Lua's `~=` (inequality). Left-associative chain.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses parse_bitwise_shift as left. Loops checking each relational
token type; on match consumes, recurses parse_bitwise_shift for right
operand, builds LUA_BINARY_OP with operator spelling, rebinds left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_relational" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse relational expressions (<, >, <=, >=, ~=, ==).
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_bitwise_shift with parser_ptr

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LT is equal to 1:
            Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
            proc ast_node_set_value with node, "<"
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
            Let right be proc parse_bitwise_shift with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
            Set left to node
        Otherwise:
            If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_GT is equal to 1:
                Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
                proc ast_node_set_value with node, ">"
                proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
                Set right to proc parse_bitwise_shift with parser_ptr
                proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
                Set left to node
            Otherwise:
                If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LT_EQ is equal to 1:
                    Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
                    proc ast_node_set_value with node, "<="
                    proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
                    Set right to proc parse_bitwise_shift with parser_ptr
                    proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
                    Set left to node
                Otherwise:
                    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_GT_EQ is equal to 1:
                        Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
                        proc ast_node_set_value with node, ">="
                        proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
                        Set right to proc parse_bitwise_shift with parser_ptr
                        proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
                        Set left to node
                    Otherwise:
                        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_TILDE_EQ is equal to 1:
                            Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
                            proc ast_node_set_value with node, "~="
                            proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
                            Set right to proc parse_bitwise_shift with parser_ptr
                            proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
                            Set left to node
                        Otherwise:
                            If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_EQ_EQ is equal to 1:
                                Set node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
                                proc ast_node_set_value with node, "=="
                                proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
                                Set right to proc parse_bitwise_shift with parser_ptr
                                proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
                                Set left to node
                            Otherwise:
                                Set continue to 0
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bitwise AND `&` layer, sitting between relational and bitwise XOR in
Lua's precedence table. Left-associative.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses parse_relational as left. Loops on TOKEN_AMPERSAND consuming,
recursing for right, wrapping in LUA_BINARY_OP value "&", rebinding
left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_bitwise_and" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse bitwise AND expressions (&).
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_relational with parser_ptr

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_AMPERSAND is equal to 1:
            Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
            proc ast_node_set_value with node, "&"
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
            Let right be proc parse_relational with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
            Set left to node
        Otherwise:
            Set continue to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bitwise XOR `~` (binary form, distinct from unary `~` complement).
Sits between bitwise AND and bitwise OR. Left-associative.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses parse_bitwise_and as left. Loops on TOKEN_TILDE consuming,
recursing for right, wrapping in LUA_BINARY_OP value "~", rebinding
left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_bitwise_xor" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse bitwise XOR expressions (~).
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_bitwise_and with parser_ptr

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_TILDE is equal to 1:
            Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
            proc ast_node_set_value with node, "~"
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
            Let right be proc parse_bitwise_and with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
            Set left to node
        Otherwise:
            Set continue to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bitwise OR `|` is the lowest-precedence bitwise operator. Above it
sit only the short-circuit logical operators (`and`, `or`).
Left-associative.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses parse_bitwise_xor as left. Loops on TOKEN_PIPE consuming,
recursing for right, wrapping in LUA_BINARY_OP value "|", rebinding
left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_bitwise_or" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse bitwise OR expressions (|).
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_bitwise_xor with parser_ptr

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_PIPE is equal to 1:
            Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
            proc ast_node_set_value with node, "|"
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
            Let right be proc parse_bitwise_xor with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
            Set left to node
        Otherwise:
            Set continue to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua's short-circuit `and` operator. Binds tighter than `or`. Left-
associative. Semantically distinct from bitwise AND — `and` returns
either the first falsy operand or the last operand.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses parse_bitwise_or as left. Loops on TOKEN_AND consuming,
recursing parse_bitwise_or for right, wrapping in LUA_BINARY_OP
value "and", rebinding left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_logical_and" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse logical AND expressions (and).
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_bitwise_or with parser_ptr

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_AND is equal to 1:
            Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
            proc ast_node_set_value with node, "and"
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
            Let right be proc parse_bitwise_or with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
            Set left to node
        Otherwise:
            Set continue to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua's `or` operator — lowest-precedence binary operator. Returns the
first truthy operand or the last operand. Left-associative.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses parse_logical_and as left. Loops on TOKEN_OR consuming,
recursing parse_logical_and for right, wrapping in LUA_BINARY_OP
value "or", rebinding left.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_logical_or" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse logical OR expressions (or).
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_logical_and with parser_ptr

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_OR is equal to 1:
            Let node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BINARY_OP
            proc ast_node_set_value with node, "or"
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, left
            Let right be proc parse_logical_and with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with node, right
            Set left to node
        Otherwise:
            Set continue to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public expression entry that starts the precedence ladder at the
lowest level (`or`). Every parser helper that needs a sub-expression
calls into here so the full precedence chain is honoured.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single forwarding call into parse_logical_or.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_expression" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a complete expression following Lua precedence rules.
    @End Reasoning

    Return proc parse_logical_or with parser_ptr
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Table Constructor Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lua table constructors mix positional and hash entries. Three field
forms: `[key] = value`, `name = value`, and bare `value` (implicit
next array index).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `{`. Builds LUA_TABLE_CONSTRUCTOR. Loops until `}`: if
TOKEN_LBRACKET, parses `[key] = value` field; else-if identifier
followed by `=`, parses `name = value` field; else parses positional
expression. Each field becomes a child LUA_TABLE_FIELD node. Consumes
comma or semicolon separator. Closes with `}`.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_table_constructor" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a Lua table constructor: {field1, field2, [key] = value, key = value}.
    @End Reasoning

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE, "Expected '{'"

    Let table_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_TABLE_CONSTRUCTOR

    Note: Parse fields
    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE is equal to 1:
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            Note: Check for [key] = value
            If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET is equal to 1:
                proc advance with parser_ptr
                Let key_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
                proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET, "Expected ']' after key"
                proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_EQ, "Expected '=' after key"
                Let value_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr

                Let field_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_TABLE_FIELD_INDEXED
                proc ast_node_add_child with field_node, key_expr
                proc ast_node_add_child with field_node, value_expr
                proc ast_node_add_child with table_node, field_node
            Otherwise:
                Note: Check for name = value
                If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER is equal to 1:
                    Let peek_next be proc peek_token with parser_ptr, 1
                    Let peek_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be peek_next

                    If peek_tok.token_type is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EQ:
                        Let name_token be proc advance with parser_ptr
                        Let name_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be name_token
                        proc advance with parser_ptr  Note: Skip '='
                        Set value_expr to proc parse_expression with parser_ptr

                        Set field_node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_TABLE_FIELD_NAMED
                        Let name_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
                        proc ast_node_set_value with name_node, name_tok.lexeme
                        proc ast_node_add_child with field_node, name_node
                        proc ast_node_add_child with field_node, value_expr
                        proc ast_node_add_child with table_node, field_node
                    Otherwise:
                        Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
                        Set field_node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_TABLE_FIELD
                        proc ast_node_add_child with field_node, expr
                        proc ast_node_add_child with table_node, field_node
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    Set expr to proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
                    Set field_node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_TABLE_FIELD
                    proc ast_node_add_child with field_node, expr
                    proc ast_node_add_child with table_node, field_node
                End If
            End If

            Note: Check for field separator (, or ; or nothing)
            If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 1:
                Note: Continue
            Otherwise:
                If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON is equal to 1:
                    Note: Continue
                Otherwise:
                    Note: No separator, check if we're at end
                    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE is equal to 0:
                        Note: More fields without separator - Lua allows this at end
                        Set continue to 0
                    End If
                End If
            End If

            Note: Check for closing brace
            If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE is equal to 1:
                Set continue to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE, "Expected '}' after table fields"
    Return table_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Function Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Anonymous function values: `function(p1, p2, ...) body end`. Used in
expression position; named function statements have their own helper.
The vararg `...` may appear as the final parameter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Caller has already consumed the `function` keyword. Consumes `(`,
parses comma-separated parameter names (or `...`) into a parameter
list child. Consumes `)`. Parses body via parse_block. Consumes
`end`. Returns LUA_FUNCTION_EXPRESSION node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_function_expression" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a function expression: function(params) body end.
    @End Reasoning

    Let func_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_FUNCTION_EXPRESSION

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN, "Expected '(' after 'function'"

    Note: Parse parameters
    Let params be proc create_ast_node with LUA_PARAMETER_LIST

    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN is equal to 0:
        Let continue be 1
        While continue is equal to 1:
            If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DOT_DOT_DOT is equal to 1:
                proc advance with parser_ptr
                Let vararg_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_VARARG
                proc ast_node_set_value with vararg_node, "..."
                proc ast_node_add_child with params, vararg_node
                Set continue to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let param_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected parameter name"
                Let param_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be param_token

                Let param_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
                proc ast_node_set_value with param_node, param_tok.lexeme
                proc ast_node_add_child with params, param_node

                If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 0:
                    Set continue to 0
                End If
            End If
        End While
    End If

    proc ast_node_add_child with func_node, params
    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')' after parameters"

    Note: Parse body
    Let body be proc parse_block with parser_ptr
    proc ast_node_add_child with func_node, body

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_END, "Expected 'end' after function body"

    Return func_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua function calls accept three argument-list forms: parenthesised
list, single string literal (`fn"str"`), or single table constructor
(`fn{...}`). The string and table forms are syntactic sugar for a
single-argument call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds LUA_ARGUMENT_LIST. If current is LPAREN: consumes it, parses
comma-separated expressions, consumes RPAREN. If STRING: appends a
single literal-expression child. If LBRACE: appends a single
table-constructor child. Returns the populated argument list node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_argument_list" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a function argument list.
    @End Reasoning

    Let args be proc create_ast_node with LUA_ARGUMENT_LIST

    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN is equal to 0:
        Let continue be 1
        While continue is equal to 1:
            Let arg_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with args, arg_expr

            If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 0:
                Set continue to 0
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Return args
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Statement Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lua's if statement supports a fully-fledged elseif chain. The parser
keeps the elseif arms flat in the AST (condition/block pairs as
siblings) for readability and downstream simplicity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `if`. Parses condition expression, expects `then`, parses
then-block. Loops on TOKEN_ELSEIF: each iteration parses condition
+ `then` + block, attaching as paired children. If TOKEN_ELSE
present, consumes and parses the final else block. Consumes `end`.
Returns LUA_IF_STATEMENT.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_if_statement" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse an if statement: if condition then block [elseif condition then block]* [else block] end.
    @End Reasoning

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IF, "Expected 'if'"

    Let if_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IF_STATEMENT

    Note: Parse condition
    Let condition be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
    proc ast_node_add_child with if_node, condition

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_THEN, "Expected 'then' after condition"

    Note: Parse then block
    Let then_block be proc parse_block with parser_ptr
    proc ast_node_add_child with if_node, then_block

    Note: Parse elseif clauses
    While proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_ELSEIF is equal to 1:
        proc advance with parser_ptr
        Let elseif_condition be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with if_node, elseif_condition

        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_THEN, "Expected 'then' after elseif condition"

        Let elseif_block be proc parse_block with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with if_node, elseif_block
    End While

    Note: Parse else clause
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_ELSE is equal to 1:
        Let else_block be proc parse_block with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with if_node, else_block
    End If

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_END, "Expected 'end' after if statement"

    Return if_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua's while loop uses `do`/`end` rather than braces. Head-tested:
the condition is checked before each iteration.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `while`. Parses condition expression. Expects `do`. Parses
body via parse_block. Expects `end`. Returns LUA_WHILE_STATEMENT with
condition + body as children.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_while_statement" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a while statement: while condition do block end.
    @End Reasoning

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_WHILE, "Expected 'while'"

    Let while_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_WHILE_STATEMENT

    Note: Parse condition
    Let condition be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
    proc ast_node_add_child with while_node, condition

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DO, "Expected 'do' after while condition"

    Note: Parse body
    Let body be proc parse_block with parser_ptr
    proc ast_node_add_child with while_node, body

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_END, "Expected 'end' after while body"

    Return while_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua's tail-tested loop: `repeat body until cond`. The condition is
checked AFTER each iteration, so the body always runs at least once.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `repeat`. Parses body via parse_block. Expects `until`.
Parses condition expression. Returns LUA_REPEAT_STATEMENT with body
+ condition as children.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_repeat_statement" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a repeat statement: repeat block until condition.
    @End Reasoning

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_REPEAT, "Expected 'repeat'"

    Let repeat_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_REPEAT_STATEMENT

    Note: Parse body
    Let body be proc parse_block with parser_ptr
    proc ast_node_add_child with repeat_node, body

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_UNTIL, "Expected 'until' after repeat body"

    Note: Parse condition
    Let condition be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
    proc ast_node_add_child with repeat_node, condition

    Return repeat_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua has two for-loop forms: numeric (`for i = start, stop[, step]
do ... end`) and generic (`for k, v in iterator do ... end`). The
parser disambiguates by looking at the token after the loop
variable: `=` -> numeric, `,` or `in` -> generic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `for`. Parses first identifier as loop variable. Peeks for
`=` (numeric form): parses start, stop, optional step expressions
separated by commas; consumes `do`, body via parse_block, `end`;
emits LUA_NUMERIC_FOR_STATEMENT. Otherwise (generic form): parses
additional names until `in`, then comma-separated iterator
expressions; consumes `do`, body, `end`; emits LUA_GENERIC_FOR_STATEMENT.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_for_statement" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a for statement (numeric or generic).
    Numeric: for i = start, end [, step] do block end
    Generic: for var1, var2 in exp1, exp2 do block end
    @End Reasoning

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_FOR, "Expected 'for'"

    Note: Parse variable names
    Let names be proc create_ast_node with LUA_NAME_LIST
    Let name_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected variable name"
    Let name_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be name_token

    Let first_var be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
    proc ast_node_set_value with first_var, name_tok.lexeme
    proc ast_node_add_child with names, first_var

    Note: Check for numeric or generic for
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_EQ is equal to 1:
        Note: Numeric for
        proc advance with parser_ptr

        Let for_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_FOR_NUMERIC
        proc ast_node_add_child with for_node, first_var

        Note: Parse start expression
        Let start_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with for_node, start_expr

        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA, "Expected ',' after start expression"

        Note: Parse end expression
        Let end_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with for_node, end_expr

        Note: Parse optional step expression
        If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 1:
            Let step_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with for_node, step_expr
        End If

        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DO, "Expected 'do' after for expressions"

        Note: Parse body
        Let body be proc parse_block with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with for_node, body

        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_END, "Expected 'end' after for body"

        Return for_node
    Otherwise:
        Note: Generic for
        Note: Parse additional variables
        While proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 1:
            Let var_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected variable name"
            Let var_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be var_token

            Let var_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
            proc ast_node_set_value with var_node, var_tok.lexeme
            proc ast_node_add_child with names, var_node
        End While

        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IN, "Expected 'in' after variable list"

        Set for_node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_FOR_GENERIC
        proc ast_node_add_child with for_node, names

        Note: Parse iterator expressions
        Let exprs be proc create_ast_node with LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST
        Let first_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with exprs, first_expr

        While proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 1:
            Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with exprs, expr
        End While

        proc ast_node_add_child with for_node, exprs

        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DO, "Expected 'do' after iterator expressions"

        Note: Parse body
        Set body to proc parse_block with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with for_node, body

        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_END, "Expected 'end' after for body"

        Return for_node
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Named function declaration: `function name body end` or
`function obj:method body end`. The method-call form gets an implicit
`self` first parameter so the AST records that distinction via a
metadata flag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `function`. Reads name (possibly dotted: `a.b.c`). If a `:`
follows, captures method name and marks the node as a method
declaration (implicit self). Parses parameter list inside `()`. Parses
body via parse_block. Consumes `end`. Returns LUA_FUNCTION_STATEMENT.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_function_statement" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a function declaration: function name(params) body end.
    Also handles: function table.field(params) body end and function table:method(params) body end.
    @End Reasoning

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION, "Expected 'function'"

    Let func_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_FUNCTION

    Note: Parse function name (can be dotted or with colon for methods)
    Let name_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected function name"
    Let name_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be name_token

    Let name_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
    proc ast_node_set_value with name_node, name_tok.lexeme

    Note: Handle table.field or table:method syntax
    Let is_method be 0
    While proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DOT is equal to 1:
        proc advance with parser_ptr
        Let field_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected field name after '.'"
        Let field_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be field_token

        Let field_access be proc create_ast_node with LUA_FIELD_ACCESS
        proc ast_node_add_child with field_access, name_node

        Let field_name be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
        proc ast_node_set_value with field_name, field_tok.lexeme
        proc ast_node_add_child with field_access, field_name

        Set name_node to field_access
    End While

    Note: Check for method syntax with :
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COLON is equal to 1:
        Let method_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected method name after ':'"
        Let method_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be method_token

        Set field_access to proc create_ast_node with LUA_FIELD_ACCESS
        proc ast_node_add_child with field_access, name_node

        Let method_name be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
        proc ast_node_set_value with method_name, method_tok.lexeme
        proc ast_node_add_child with field_access, method_name

        Set name_node to field_access
        Set is_method to 1
    End If

    proc ast_node_add_child with func_node, name_node

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN, "Expected '(' after function name"

    Note: Parse parameters (implicit 'self' for methods)
    Let params be proc create_ast_node with LUA_PARAMETER_LIST

    If is_method is equal to 1:
        Note: Add implicit 'self' parameter
        Let self_param be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
        proc ast_node_set_value with self_param, "self"
        proc ast_node_add_child with params, self_param
    End If

    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN is equal to 0:
        Let continue be 1
        While continue is equal to 1:
            If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DOT_DOT_DOT is equal to 1:
                proc advance with parser_ptr
                Let vararg_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_VARARG
                proc ast_node_set_value with vararg_node, "..."
                proc ast_node_add_child with params, vararg_node
                Set continue to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let param_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected parameter name"
                Let param_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be param_token

                Let param_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
                proc ast_node_set_value with param_node, param_tok.lexeme
                proc ast_node_add_child with params, param_node

                If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 0:
                    Set continue to 0
                End If
            End If
        End While
    End If

    proc ast_node_add_child with func_node, params
    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')' after parameters"

    Note: Parse body
    Let body be proc parse_block with parser_ptr
    proc ast_node_add_child with func_node, body

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_END, "Expected 'end' after function body"

    Return func_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
`local` introduces lexically-scoped bindings: variable declarations
(`local name [, name]* [= expr [, expr]*]`) or local function
declarations (`local function name(...) body end`). The parser
disambiguates via lookahead.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `local`. If next is TOKEN_FUNCTION, delegates to a local-
function path (parses name + params + body). Otherwise parses
comma-separated name list, optional `=` + comma-separated expression
list. Returns LUA_LOCAL_STATEMENT with names and values as children.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_local_statement" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a local declaration: local name1, name2 = exp1, exp2.
    @End Reasoning

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LOCAL, "Expected 'local'"

    Note: Check for local function
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION is equal to 1:
        proc advance with parser_ptr

        Let func_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_FUNCTION

        Let name_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected function name"
        Let name_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be name_token

        Let name_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
        proc ast_node_set_value with name_node, name_tok.lexeme
        proc ast_node_add_child with func_node, name_node

        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN, "Expected '(' after function name"

        Note: Parse parameters
        Let params be proc create_ast_node with LUA_PARAMETER_LIST

        If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN is equal to 0:
            Let continue be 1
            While continue is equal to 1:
                If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DOT_DOT_DOT is equal to 1:
                    proc advance with parser_ptr
                    Let vararg_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_VARARG
                    proc ast_node_set_value with vararg_node, "..."
                    proc ast_node_add_child with params, vararg_node
                    Set continue to 0
                Otherwise:
                    Let param_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected parameter name"
                    Let param_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be param_token

                    Let param_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
                    proc ast_node_set_value with param_node, param_tok.lexeme
                    proc ast_node_add_child with params, param_node

                    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 0:
                        Set continue to 0
                    End If
                End If
            End While
        End If

        proc ast_node_add_child with func_node, params
        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')' after parameters"

        Note: Parse body
        Let body be proc parse_block with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with func_node, body

        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_END, "Expected 'end' after function body"

        Note: Mark as local in metadata
        Let local_decl be proc create_ast_node with LUA_LOCAL_DECLARATION
        proc ast_node_add_child with local_decl, func_node

        Return local_decl
    End If

    Note: Regular local variable declaration
    Let local_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_LOCAL_DECLARATION

    Note: Parse variable names
    Let names be proc create_ast_node with LUA_NAME_LIST
    Set name_token to proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected variable name"
    Set name_tok to name_token

    Let first_var be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
    proc ast_node_set_value with first_var, name_tok.lexeme
    proc ast_node_add_child with names, first_var

    While proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 1:
        Let var_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected variable name"
        Let var_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be var_token

        Let var_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_IDENTIFIER
        proc ast_node_set_value with var_node, var_tok.lexeme
        proc ast_node_add_child with names, var_node
    End While

    proc ast_node_add_child with local_node, names

    Note: Parse optional initializers
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_EQ is equal to 1:
        Let exprs be proc create_ast_node with LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST
        Let first_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with exprs, first_expr

        While proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 1:
            Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with exprs, expr
        End While

        proc ast_node_add_child with local_node, exprs
    End If

    Return local_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
`return [expr [, expr]*]` — Lua allows zero or more return values.
The statement must be the last in its block (enforced by the lexer/
parser elsewhere), and may be followed by an optional `;`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `return`. If next token can start an expression (not `end`,
`else`, `elseif`, `until`, EOF, or `;`), parses comma-separated
expression list. Optional `;` is consumed. Returns LUA_RETURN_STATEMENT.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_return_statement" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a return statement: return [exp1, exp2, ...].
    @End Reasoning

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RETURN, "Expected 'return'"

    Let return_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_RETURN_STATEMENT

    Note: Check if there are return values
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_END is equal to 0:
        If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_ELSEIF is equal to 0:
            If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_ELSE is equal to 0:
                If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_UNTIL is equal to 0:
                    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON is equal to 0:
                        If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_EOF is equal to 0:
                            Note: Parse return values
                            Let exprs be proc create_ast_node with LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST
                            Let first_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
                            proc ast_node_add_child with exprs, first_expr

                            While proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 1:
                                Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
                                proc ast_node_add_child with exprs, expr
                            End While

                            proc ast_node_add_child with return_node, exprs
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return return_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua 5.2+ label syntax `::name::` introduces a goto target. Used in
combination with `goto name` for limited unstructured control flow
(e.g. continue-like behaviour).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the opening `::`. Expects an identifier (the label name).
Consumes the closing `::`. Returns LUA_LABEL_STATEMENT with the name
in the value field.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_label_statement" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a label statement: ::name::.
    @End Reasoning

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON, "Expected '::'"

    Let label_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected label name"
    Let label_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be label_token

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON, "Expected '::' after label name"

    Let label_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_LABEL_STATEMENT
    proc ast_node_set_value with label_node, label_tok.lexeme

    Return label_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
`goto name` companion to label statements. Lua's scoping rules
restrict goto-target visibility, but the parser does not enforce them
— that's a semantic analysis concern downstream.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `goto`. Expects an identifier (the target label name).
Returns LUA_GOTO_STATEMENT with the name in the value field.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_goto_statement" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a goto statement: goto name.
    @End Reasoning

    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_GOTO, "Expected 'goto'"

    Let label_token be proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected label name"
    Let label_tok as Lexer.LuaToken be label_token

    Let goto_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_GOTO_STATEMENT
    proc ast_node_set_value with goto_node, label_tok.lexeme

    Return goto_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua's "expression statement" position can be either a function-call
expression (used as a statement) or an assignment `lhs[, lhs]* = expr
[, expr]*`. The parser builds the LHS as an expression first, then
disambiguates by looking for `=` (assignment) or treating a
function-call form as a statement directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses a postfix expression as the first LHS candidate. If next is
`,`, accumulates more comma-separated LHS expressions. If next is
`=`, consumes it, parses comma-separated RHS expressions, builds
LUA_ASSIGNMENT_STATEMENT with lhs-list and rhs-list. If first LHS
was a function call (LUA_FUNCTION_CALL or LUA_METHOD_CALL), treats it
as a call statement. Otherwise records a parser error.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_assignment_or_call" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse an assignment or function call statement.
    This is complex because we need to parse the left side as expressions first,
    then determine if it's an assignment or a call.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Parse first expression
    Let first_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr

    Note: Check if it's an assignment
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_EQ is equal to 1:
        Note: Assignment
        Let assign_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_ASSIGNMENT

        Note: Parse left-hand side list
        Let lhs be proc create_ast_node with LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST
        proc ast_node_add_child with lhs, first_expr

        While proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 1:
            Let var_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with lhs, var_expr
        End While

        proc ast_node_add_child with assign_node, lhs

        proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_EQ, "Expected '='"

        Note: Parse right-hand side list
        Let rhs be proc create_ast_node with LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST
        Let first_rhs be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
        proc ast_node_add_child with rhs, first_rhs

        While proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 1:
            Let rhs_expr be proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with rhs, rhs_expr
        End While

        proc ast_node_add_child with assign_node, rhs

        Return assign_node
    Otherwise:
        Note: Check if it's an additional assignment target
        If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 1:
            Note: Multiple assignment targets
            Set assign_node to proc create_ast_node with LUA_ASSIGNMENT

            Set lhs to proc create_ast_node with LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST
            proc ast_node_add_child with lhs, first_expr

            While proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 1:
                Set var_expr to proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
                proc ast_node_add_child with lhs, var_expr
            End While

            proc ast_node_add_child with assign_node, lhs

            proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_EQ, "Expected '=' after variable list"

            Note: Parse right-hand side list
            Set rhs to proc create_ast_node with LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST
            Set first_rhs to proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
            proc ast_node_add_child with rhs, first_rhs

            While proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA is equal to 1:
                Set rhs_expr to proc parse_expression with parser_ptr
                proc ast_node_add_child with rhs, rhs_expr
            End While

            proc ast_node_add_child with assign_node, rhs

            Return assign_node
        Otherwise:
            Note: Just a function call or expression statement
            Return first_expr
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Statement-level dispatcher. Maps Lua keywords to their dedicated
parse_* helpers. Falls back to parse_assignment_or_call for the
expression-statement / assignment residual case.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current token type. Sequential dispatch: IF, WHILE, REPEAT, FOR,
FUNCTION, LOCAL, RETURN, BREAK (inline simple node), DO (block
with `do`/`end`), DOUBLE_COLON (label), GOTO. Anything else delegates
to parse_assignment_or_call.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_statement" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a single statement.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Semicolon (empty statement)
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON is equal to 1:
        Note: Empty statement - return nil
        Let empty_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_NIL_LITERAL
        Return empty_node
    End If

    Note: If statement
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_IF is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_if_statement with parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: While statement
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_WHILE is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_while_statement with parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Repeat statement
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_REPEAT is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_repeat_statement with parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: For statement
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_FOR is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_for_statement with parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Function declaration
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_function_statement with parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Local declaration
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_LOCAL is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_local_statement with parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Return statement
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_RETURN is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_return_statement with parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Break statement
    If proc match with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_BREAK is equal to 1:
        Let break_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BREAK_STATEMENT
        Return break_node
    End If

    Note: Label statement
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_label_statement with parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Goto statement
    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_GOTO is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_goto_statement with parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Assignment or function call
    Return proc parse_assignment_or_call with parser_ptr
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Block and Program Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A sequence of statements terminating at a block-end token (`end`,
`else`, `elseif`, `until`, EOF). Block-end detection is centralised
here so every block-bearing construct (function bodies, control-flow
arms) uses the same terminator logic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds LUA_BLOCK. Loops while current token is not a terminator
(end/else/elseif/until/EOF). Each iteration parses a statement via
parse_statement; if non-zero, attaches as child. Returns the block.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_block" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a block of statements.
    @End Reasoning

    Let block_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_BLOCK

    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        Note: Check for block terminators
        If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_END is equal to 1:
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_ELSEIF is equal to 1:
                Set continue to 0
            Otherwise:
                If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_ELSE is equal to 1:
                    Set continue to 0
                Otherwise:
                    If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_UNTIL is equal to 1:
                        Set continue to 0
                    Otherwise:
                        If proc check with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_EOF is equal to 1:
                            Set continue to 0
                        Otherwise:
                            Let stmt be proc parse_statement with parser_ptr
                            proc ast_node_add_child with block_node, stmt
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return block_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A Lua source file is itself a block (the chunk). This helper just
wraps parse_block with a LUA_PROGRAM root node so downstream tools
can distinguish file-level from nested blocks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds LUA_PROGRAM. Calls parse_block; attaches the resulting block
as the program's only child. Returns the program node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_program" takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse the entire Lua program (top-level block).
    @End Reasoning

    Let program_node be proc create_ast_node with LUA_PROGRAM

    Let block be proc parse_block with parser_ptr
    proc ast_node_add_child with program_node, block

    Note: Expect EOF
    proc consume with parser_ptr, Lexer.TOKEN_EOF, "Expected end of file"

    Return program_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public top-level entry point that all consumers call. Delegates to
parse_program. Kept as a thin alias so the public name stays stable
even if the internal driver is renamed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
